text:
Westdeen  markets  the  Dongara  limesand  direct  from  the  pit  as  agricultural  lime  to 
 farmers  through  the  northern  wheatbelt.    The  farmers  spread  it  on  their  paddocks  to 
 neutralise soil acidity formed as a consequence of intensive farming.  Field trials located 
 throughout the central and northern wheatbelt are used to demonstrate the economic 
 value of applying limesand to acid soils.  This activity promotes liming to farmers and 
 underpins Westdeen’s Dongara operations. 
 The extraction operation on M70/309 is extremely simple.  A front-end loader is used to 
 dig limesand from the pit face.  The loader tips the sand directly into trucks that deliver 
 direct to farms.  Occasionally, sand is screened to remove sticks prior to loading onto 
 trucks.   The  pit  face  advances  north  each  year  as  sand  is  progressively  removed.  
 Limesand is extracted down to the level of the adjacent coastal plain. 
 Some  8929  tonnes  of  limesand  were  loaded  and  sold  from  M70/309  through  the 
 2006/2007 reporting period.  This is only 38% of the 23,072 tonnes loaded and sold in 
 the previous year.  Drought in the market area has impacted to a certain extent on lime 
 sales,  however,  the  emergence  of  ‘cut  price,  load  yourself’  operations  in  nearby 
 limesand  deposits  is  the  major  influence.    Despite  losing  sales,  our  company  policy 
 remains as always.  We believe it is imperative, especially from a safety perspective to 
 engage  the  services  of  professional  contract  loader  operators,  to  load  limesand  into 
 trucks for delivery into the wheatbelt.  To this end, we must pay a reasonable fee for 
 contract loading services.  The emergence of cut-price operations that simply leave 
 an old loader (often without approved load cells) on site is a serious safety issue 
 and needs to be addressed.   
 The high quality of the limesand resource within M70/309 contains adequate reserves to 
 fully service agricultural demand over the next 5 to 10 years.  There is also increasing 
 demand for limesand to be used as fill sand for much of the new building development 
 that is occurring in coastal towns in the region.  Our company policy is to refrain from 
 using  premium  quality  limesand  as  fill  sand,  however  we  recognise  the  demand.  
 Bearing this in mind, we have recently applied for a new tenement (M70/1271) that is a 
 substantial dune system, advancing rather rapidly to the extent it will soon cover over 
 Kailis Drive.  Westdeen aims to develop this deposit to supply fill sand in Dongara, and 
 prevent the local shire from bearing the expense of clearing Kailis drive several times 
 each  season.    Reserves  of  limesand  on  M70/310  will  sustain  operations  beyond  the 
 foreseeable future.

text:
Mining  on  M70/309  commenced  in  1988.    Relatively  small  tonnages  were  mined 
 through  the  late  1980’s  and  early  1990’s  due  an  ongoing  rural  recession  and  poor 
 market  acceptance.    Through  the  late  1990’s,  however,  there  was  a  marked 
 improvement  in  the  rural  economy  with  improved  farming  technology,  increased  crop 
 yields  and  higher  export  grain  prices.    This,  and  the  positive  extension  efforts  on  the 
 need  to  lime  acid  soils  from  the  Agriculture  Department  and  Westdeen’s  continuing 
 research and promotion saw a marked increase in demand for limesand. 
 Despite these gains, demand for Westdeen’s Dongara limesand has been lower than 
 expected.    Sales  in  any  year  remain  susceptible  to  increasing  competition  from 
 alternative suppliers, seasonal and market conditions for farm produce. 
 The  tenement  group  is  located  south  of  Dongara  and  west  of  the  Brand  Highway.  
 Mining  lease  70/309  is  located  immediately  south  east  of  the  Port  Denison  townsite. 
 Mining lease 70/310 is located around 17 kilometres to the south of Dongara townsite 
 between the Brand Highway and the Geraldton Eneabba railway line.  These locations 
 are shown by map and Tengraph plan in Appendices 1 and 2 respectively.   
 The sand dunes contained within the two Mining Leases (309 and 310) were formed in 
 relatively  recent  times,  probably  around  5,000  years  ago.    They  are  rich  in  calcium 
 carbonate (averaging around 89%) and magnesium carbonate (averaging around 6%) 
 reflecting their origin from the marine shells and corals that inhabited the shallow waters 
 along this section of the West Australian coastline.  Driven by prevailing biological and 
 physical  (climatic,  ocean  and  coastal)  cycles,  the  calcium  rich  marine  materials  were 
 progressively broken down into small fragments and washed up onto the beaches.  The 
 fine sand material was then blown into parabolic aeolian dunes.  As the mobile front of 
 these dunes was blown in a NNE direction by the prevailing winds it trailed dune ridges 
 on  either  side.    These  ridges  and  the  intervening  areas  of  coastal  plain  were 
 progressively vegetated and stabilised.  This process is continuing to varying degrees at

6.  ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT 
 Routine management involves regular visits to the tenement to ensure that the required 
 standards of environmental management are maintained.  This involves: 
 • inspecting the access track for erosion and weeds; 
 • inspecting the pit and adjacent areas for erosion, regrowth and weeds; 
 • monitoring the rehabilitation of previously disturbed areas;  
 • monitoring the limesand dunes for drift; and, 
 • meeting with the resident Mine Manager regarding significant issues.  
 Westdeen Holdings maintains an ongoing program of advertising, field days, seminars, 
 client  visits  etc  to  promote  the  use  of  limesand  generally,  and  the  availability  of  high 
 quality material from Dongara for farmers in the northern market area.
